# Event window math

## Why this rule exists

PR #38 had three findings on the same line of code, on three different
files, all the same bug: `[polledEvt, ...prev].slice(-150)` puts the
new event at the **front** and then keeps the **last** 150, which means
once `prev` has 149 items, the new event is dropped on the next call.

The mistake compounded because the bug was copy-pasted from one page
to another. None of three reviewers / authors caught it; the agent
shipped it three times.

## Rule

For any "keep newest N events" buffer, write it as:

```ts
// keep last N, newest at the bottom
[...prev, newEvent].slice(-N)
```

For "keep newest N events, newest at the top":

```ts
// keep first N, newest at the top
[newEvent, ...prev].slice(0, N)
```

**Never mix `[new, ...prev]` with `slice(-N)` or `[...prev, new]` with
`slice(0, N)`.** They drop the wrong end.

When in doubt, write a unit test that adds N+1 events and asserts the
last one is retained.

## Concrete example in this repo

```ts
// frontend/src/pages/ResearchPageV2.tsx — current correct usage
setTraceEvents((prev) => sortEventsChronological([...prev, polledEvt].slice(-150)));
```

## Pre-commit check

For any new event buffer:
- [ ] Does the slice direction match the spread direction?
- [ ] Is there a unit test that pushes more than the limit and asserts
  the most recent event survives?
- [ ] If you copy-pasted the buffer logic from another file, did you
  re-verify it's correct in both places? (PR #38 had the bug copy-pasted
  to three files because the original was wrong.)
